13 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
14 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
15 Article – Education
16 2–104.
17 (a) The following employees shall be appointed to positions in the Department:
18 (1) [No more than three] ANY Deputy State Superintendents of Schools;
19 (2) Any assistant State superintendents and directors authorized by the
20 State Board and provided in the State budget; and
21 (3) Any other employees to fill positions authorized by the State Board and
22 provided in the State budget.
23 9.5–118.
24 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
25 INDICATED.
26 (2) (I) “APPLICANT” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS APPLYING FOR
27 A POSITION INVOLVING DIRECT CONTACT WITH CHILDREN IN A CHILD CARE
28 FACILITY.
29 (II) “APPLICANT” INCLUDES A VOLUNTEER OR OTHER
30 INDIVIDUALS WHO MAY BE SUBJECT TO FEDERALLY REQUIRED BACKGROUND
31 CHECKS.

HOUSE BILL 635 3
1 (3) “CENTRAL REPOSITORY” MEANS THE CRIMINAL JUSTICE
2 INFORMATION SYSTEM CENTRAL REPOSITORY OF THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC
3 SAFETY AND CORRECTIONAL SERVICES.
4 (4) “CHILD CARE FACILITY” MEANS A CHILD CARE FACILITY
5 IDENTIFIED UNDER § 5–551 OF THE FAMILY LAW ARTICLE REGISTERED FAMILY
6 CHILD CARE HOME, A REGISTERED LARGE FAMILY CHILD CARE HOME, A LICENSED
7 CHILD CARE CENTER, OR A CHILD CARE CENTER THAT HOLDS A LETTER OF
8 COMPLIANCE.
9 (B) AN APPLICANT WHO IS SEEKING A POSITION INVOLVING DIRECT
10 CONTACT WITH CHILDREN AT A CHILD CARE FACILITY SHALL SUBMIT TO A CRIMINAL
11 HISTORY RECORDS CHECK IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 5–555 OF THE FAMILY LAW
12 ARTICLE.
13 (C) (1) (I) THE ON OR BEFORE JUNE 30, 2027, THE DEPARTMENT
14 SHALL ESTABLISH A CENTRALIZED UNIT FOR THE PROCESSING AND MANAGEMENT
15 OF INFORMATION ABOUT CRIMINAL HISTORY RECORDS CHECKS FOR APPLICANTS
16 PROVIDING CHILD CARE SERVICES.
17 (II) THE CENTRALIZED UNIT MAY BE STAFFED BY LICENSING
18 SPECIALISTS IN THE REGIONAL CHILD CARE LICENSING OFFICES THROUGHOUT THE
19 STATE.
20 (2) THE CENTRALIZED UNIT SHALL NOTIFY AN APPLICANT FOR A
21 CRIMINAL HISTORY RECORDS CHECK:
22 (I) OF THE STATUS OF THE APPLICATION WITHIN 10 DAYS
23 AFTER SUBMISSION; AND
24 (II) SUBJECT TO THE RECEIPT OF THE CRIMINAL HISTORY
25 RECORD INFORMATION FROM THE CENTRAL REPOSITORY UNDER SUBSECTION (D)
26 OF THIS SECTION, WITHIN 45 DAYS AFTER SUBMISSION THE TIME FRAME REQUIRED
27 UNDER FEDERAL LAW, OF THE APPLICANT’S ELIGIBILITY TO PROVIDE CHILD CARE
28 SERVICES IN A CHILD CARE FACILITY.
29 (D) (1) THE CENTRALIZED UNIT SHALL REVIEW AND MAINTAIN
30 BACKGROUND CHECKS COMPLETED IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 5–555 OF THE FAMILY
31 LAW ARTICLE.
32 (2) INFORMATION OBTAINED FROM THE CENTRAL REPOSITORY
33 UNDER THIS SECTION:

4 HOUSE BILL 635
1 (I) IS CONFIDENTIAL;
2 (II) MAY NOT BE DISSEMINATED WITHOUT THE EXPRESS
3 PERMISSION OF THE APPLICANT; AND
4 (III) MAY BE USED ONLY FOR THE PURPOSES AUTHORIZED BY
5 THIS TITLE.
6 (E) (1) (I) THE CENTRALIZED UNIT MAY MAINTAIN A LIST OF
7 APPLICANTS WHO HAVE SUBMITTED A CRIMINAL HISTORY RECORDS CHECK IN
8 ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION.
9 (II) THE CENTRALIZED UNIT MAY SHARE THE NAME AND
10 STATUS OF AN APPLICANT ON THE LIST WITH:
11 1. A CHILD CARE FACILITY AT WHICH THE APPLICANT
12 SEEKS TO BE EMPLOYED OR VOLUNTEER; AND
13 2. THE APPLICANT.
14 (2) ON REQUEST BY AN APPLICANT OR A CHILD CARE FACILITY, THE
15 CENTRALIZED UNIT MAY PROVIDE WRITTEN NOTICE TO THE APPLICANT OR THE
16 CHILD CARE FACILITY THAT AN APPLICANT WHO SEEKS TO BE EMPLOYED BY OR
17 VOLUNTEER WITH THE CHILD CARE FACILITY HAS A CRIMINAL HISTORY RECORDS
18 CHECK ON FILE WITH THE DEPARTMENT.
19 9.5–404.
20 (a) The State Board shall adopt rules and regulations for licensing and operating
21 child care centers.
22 (b) These rules and regulations shall:
23 (13) Subject to subsection (c) of this section, establish probationary
24 employment qualifications for an individual who is applying for the first time to be a child
25 care teacher in a child care center in the State that serves preschool or school–age children
26 who are at least [3] 2 years old.
27 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
28 (a) The State Department of Education shall review the process for background
29 checks established under § 9.5–118 of the Education Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this
30 Act, to evaluate the efficiency and timeliness of processing applications and to identify
31 opportunities for improvement while maintaining safety and compliance with State and
32 federal law.

HOUSE BILL 635 5
1 (b) The review required under subsection (a) of this section shall include an
2 examination of:
3 (1) regulations;
4 (2) policies;
5 (3) procedures; and
6 (4) interagency coordination of background checks.
7 (c) On or before October 1, 2028, the Department shall report, in accordance with
8 § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, to the General Assembly the results of the review
9 required under subsection (a) of this section, including:
10 (1) the number of background check applications;
11 (2) data on background check processing times;
12 (3) any delays or barriers to the process; and
13 (4) any recommendations for changing State law or administrative
14 procedures.
15 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
16 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
